  <id>92077872</id>
  <body><![CDATA[Madeline - I was hoping you received my message on The Fault In Our Stars ( TFIOS). When I finished the book, I was so excited to share my excitement and joy with you! Without you having read Donna Tartt and connected to my review, I may have missed out on one of the loveliest stories I have read all year. I tried anxiously to write to you and ask and answer to clarify things for me and I think I came up with ideas on some other interests that I found out from things I studied and taught in school. I hope I did not sound like a know it all little nerd anxiously waving her hand to be called to answer questions in class! LOL! But I felt like that after I read the book and wanted to share. <br /><br />Mostly- thank you very much for enlightening me about an awesome author with more good books to read and for reminding me how wonderful my English teaching experience was when I taught Secondary English Education for 15 years. I cried because I wish I could have been a teacher to have taught that book. I wish I could have seen the students reactions , even the students that say they don't care or are too cool to read. This book could have been one of those that brought communication about important stuff and I could have slipped in learning things about, themes, conflicts, symbolism and more in a way they may never have forgotten. But, most of all , can you imagine being in the middle of augments when they try to discuss belief systems about life and death, or love and true love, or the importance of a life rather known to all or known only to make a difference by few. Then there is that metaphor for being independent or reckless or having the right to take fault for your own mistakes. That cigarette had nothing to do with a company -- at different points in that novel , that cigarette was a metaphor for independence, pride, self assurance as being a person over which there could be no control unless he decided ( which we find out in the end is a farce) . Everyone must eventually learn in life that you do not control your own Fate or Destiny , God is the only spirit with strength to control . You can't control people either, only God , and you just have to accept you can do the best you can do make things better for you and people you love. The rest is up to you controlling how you REACT to fate, circumstances and the actions of others. Augustus Waters was putting that CIGARETTE in his mouth as a flag saying, " Hey, I am a grenade " too. Don't get too close I am going to explode and I will hurt you. The same point to adults and parents, I am what I am - accept it-- babies don't smoke. Mom and Dad, if I chose to blow, it will not be your fault or anyone elses. Finally, take a look at Massif's pyramid again. What do you see there scientifically and symbolically? Then when they give into love on the Second Floor of the Hotel in Amsterdam, look up the name of that second floor, Kriekenkard ( spelling? ) was a philosopher who believed in mysticism or Existentialism. This is the belief that one can only know God through his / her own intense emotional experience. How do people prove God must exist? You can't see him, touch, or hear him. How do you know love exists ? You can't see it, touch it, hear it, ---YOU ONLY FEEL THE DEEPLY FELT CONNECTION AND EMOTIONAL CATHARSIS IN YOUR ON MIND AND BODY. Augustus once says to Hazel Grace, how will I ever see you again? He is referring to LIFE AFTER DEATH . There is so much REAL DEPTH IN THIS NOVEL ! I can't even begin to finish here. And, there is no telling what I missed.<br /><br />Madeline - there is so much more ... Now, one thing I thought about ...tell me to FO if you want. If you felt that strongly about the cigarette metaphor being bothersome, then what other symbol could Green have used. I have been trying to thing of something . What do you think? <br /><br />When you get time ... Thank you again, Dawn]]></body>
  
