        <comment>
  <id>92090895</id>
  <body><![CDATA[<i>If you felt that strongly about the cigarette metaphor being bothersome, then what other symbol could Green have used.</i><br /><br />I have no problem with Augustus employing the cigarette metaphor as a way of coping with his illness. What I have a problem with is Hazel making the point that Gus is <i>directly funding</i> an organization that causes cancer when he buys these supposed "fuck you, cancer" cigarettes, and this perfectly valid point never being addressed in the book. It's a serious flaw in Gus's character, but a necessary one - that he can believe in something so strongly, even if that belief is wrong. I would just have liked Hazel to press him more on the overarching effects of his dumb metaphor.]]></body>
  
