  <id>92099797</id>
  <body><![CDATA[I think that was the point too! Hazel kept saying how perfect Augustus was over and over compared to so many others including herself. She was so overwhelmingly flattered by him at first to even bother addressing the issue at the first meeting because she had been so charmed especially after the depressed state of isolation from which she was coming. She did sense his imperfections by the next visit. She questioned the metaphoric cigarette again and realized that was another of his imperfections besides his driving. No one can be totally perfect although we seem to think so at times. <br /><br />In this case , John Green is basing this story loosely on a girl named Esther Earl as I am sure you know. She actually had cancer of the thyroid which then led to her lung condition. Although cigarettes did not probably cause her cancer, she still would be angry because they would cause other cancers and they would have direct impact on breathing . <br /><br />Somehow John Green had to get the " DO NOT SMOKE MESSAGE IN LOUD AND CLEAR" which is maybe why he even left the point about the cigarette companies open. He may have wanted it to bug people . <br /><br />Otherwise, the act of free choice is opened. Free enterprise is opened. Freedom in genera is a big thought. Along with carrying the theme The Fault In Our Stars; we all have flaws. Even superheroes have weaknesses. <br /><br />Do you want to see the movie? Are you going to read Esther Earl's book THIS STAR WIIL KEEP SHINING ? <br /><br />Do you smoke or know people who do? If not does it bother you? <br /><br />Dawn]]></body>
  
